		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=384524"><span id=Scholar>Teleos</span></a><b><span id=Scholar><br>Scholar</span></b><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />292 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Good [3.59]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=Teleos&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p>Having lost a fight recently with all mellee down, despite having a druid and shaman rotation healing, I was interested in techniques folk use to effectively use just the right amount of mana in a such a situation. It may be too situational for any advice, but are there any basic tricks to ensuring the mana is stretched out as far as possible, and how do you avoid healing &quot;on top&quot; of another players heal? <br><br>The exact situation was a group of 65-70 players doing a fabled... monk, druid, BL, chanter, shaman. The mob was red to a 65. It was a reasonable fight, and we lost at 3pc so in a way just a few heals more would have done the job. I have been wondering if as a shaman I should be spamming Q on top of the druid heals, then switching to spot heals or big heals as the mob enraged. <br><br>The monk later thought he had mistimed his mend, so that is a further factor. Would the BL Paragon have made much difference? Perhaps it is all to complex for general advice.</p><br /><span class="sm">----------------------------</span><br />Hack that mob to bits.. get it down to ones and zeros fast!</td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8"></td><td align="right" id="fs8" >15 Replies</td></tr></table>
