		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=1286"><span id=Encyclopedia>gbaji</span></a><b><span id=Encyclopedia><br>Encyclopedia</span></b><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />9740 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Good [4.02]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=gbaji&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p>Few points on healing.<br><br>I don't believe that druids have any HoT spells, so the shaman should certainly have been using them. That alone would have stretched the mana out since the HoT will slow the apparent rate of damage down enough for the druid to use the most efficient direct heals possible.<br><br>Additionally there is absolutely nothing wrong with setting up a heal rotation, even in a single group. Something as simple as a hotkey used when each healer casts their biggest direct heals (complete with cast time) should work fine. If druid is using his semi-CH spell for instance, he'll have a message saying that he's casting and it'll take 10 seconds. Ok. 10 seconds, plus 2ish seconds recast time means 12 seconds before he can cast it again. So if the shaman is casting a 10 second heal as well, he should be starting it 6 seconds into the cast. This kind of timing will presumably max out your heal rate.<br><br>In many fights, that's not going to be needed though. The issue isn't max heal rate, but most efficient heal rate. Again. Hotkeys help terrifically. Make sure to designate a main healer. That healer hotkeys any large heals used. This allows the patch healer to toss in patch heals based on the projected damage rate and heal rate so as to keep the tank alive without wasting any mana.<br><br><br>Finally. Get a real tank. Ok. That's a semi-joke, but there's some truth to it. The higher the HPs on your tank, the more leeway you have in terms of healing efficiency. Think about it this way:<br><br>The only way two healers are bumping into eachother in terms of healing is if the total of two heals they might cast is more then the amount the tank can be healed for (resuling in wasted healing). Obviously, the higher the HPs on the tank, the less likely this will happen. This goes double for druid/shaman healing. Two clerics and botch up their CHs on any tank, but when the most you're healing is in the 3-4k range, you've got to have a fairly low HP tank for that to be a huge problem. The biggest problem most groups have with those two classes healing is that their tank is still at 60% after they drop their biggest heal spell.<br><br><br>If you'd had even an 8k buffed HP tank for that fight, you should have had zero problems in terms of wasted heal spells with a druid and shaman healing. If you did have problems, then you were likely casting your heals too soon and not alternating casts in any way. With a 10k or higher tank, you'd have been hard pressed to block eachother's heals. Again though. You've *got* to designate one as healer and one as patcher. If you don't, then you will have both healers starting a ~3k heal at 80% health, and landing both well before the tank is low enough to need two of them.</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8">Posting from San Diego, CA</td></tr></table>
