		   <table class="mform2"  border="0" cellpadding="1" cellspacing="0" width="100%">
		   <tr><td class="headerrow" colspan="2" class="mform2" valign="top" id="forumSubject">
		   <span class="sm">Posted @ Mon, Mar 28th 10:19 PM2005 </span><span id="notbold">| <span class="sm">IP: Logged</span> | <a class="sm" href="/forum.html?forum=1&mid=1112058294560715935&num=15&post=1&replyto=1112066318973594907"><img src="/shared/reply_to_thread_ico.gif" border="0" alt="Reply..." height="11" width="17" /> Reply to this</a></a>    <a name=1112066318973594907></a></small></td></tr>
		   <tr><td valign="top" id="fs8" class="mform2" ><span id="notbold">By:</span> <a href="/db/poster.html?user=1286"><span id=Encyclopedia>gbaji</span></a><b><span id=Encyclopedia><br>Encyclopedia</span></b><br /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*"/><img src="/shared/user_star_ico.gif" height="9" width="9" alt="*" /><br />9740 posts
		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Good [4.02]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=gbaji&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform2" width="100%"><p><blockquote><b id="fs8">Teleos wrote:</b><hr size="1" /><br>What can be done to manage &quot;Enrage&quot;? Is it allways at 20pc of the NPC health? Clearly we needed mana up for the additional damage here.<hr size="1" /></blockquote><br><br>Enrage can occur at some random time when the mob is low on health. On particularly long fights, I've seen mobs enrage multiple times. I do believe they generally only do it at 20% or lower (but I don't see any reason why one couldn't be programmed to do it at any time).<br><br>How you handle enrage is simple. People seem to panic about enrage as though it's this horrible thing. All enrages does is give the mob a 100% riposte chance. What this means is that every attack *from the front* of the mob will be riposted. Obviously, anyone attacking from the front will start taking some serious damage very quickly (since this is in addition to the normal damage the mob puts out).<br><br>It's nothing to panic about. The trick to enrage is knowing about it and preparing for it ahead of time. Your tank should turn the mob away from the rest of the melee force (this includes pets). When fighting a mob that enrages, you need to use raid discipline (which a lot of poeple may have never done before). The only person on the front of the mob should be the MT. Everyone else is arrayed behind it (which is a good idea anyway since you avoid normal, blocks, parries, dodges and riposts from behind anyway thus increasing your groups dps).<br><br>All you need to do when enrage hits is turn off autoattack. The MT needs to make sure he keeps agro. Everyone else can continue fighting as normal (but being *very careful not to agro the mob and make it turn on the rest of the melee force). The mistake people make when enrage hits is to panic. They think the mob suddenly is doing tons of damage so their initial reaction is to attack more forcefully. Nukers start to overnuke to try to finish the mob off quick to save the tank, this causes the mob to turn towards the nuker, which exposes the rest of the melee to his enrage and gets people killed.<br><br>Just make sure everyone who is doing melee damage is on the opposite side from the MT. Make sure the MT has and maintains agro on the mob. When enrage hits, the MT just turns off autoattack and switches to just agro stuff (I start casting stuns personally). The rest of the group should continue fighting *exactly* as they had before. There's no rush. As long as your MT turns off autoattack, he's taking no more damage then he was during the rest of the fight. What's the hurry? There's nothing to panic about. Just keep damaging the mob and let the MT keep agro and everything works out fine. You'll either finish off the mob with normal dps, or it'll come out of enrage and the MT can resume attacking. In either case, just keep doing what you were doing for the first 80% of the mobs health.<br><br><br>Enrage is only a problem for those who don't know how it works, and/or don't use good position discipline when fighting. If you are on the same side of the mob as the MT, you're in the wrong spot. It's really that easy. And you should be doing that on *every* mob, not just those that enrage. Get in the habit of positioning your melee correctly, and you'll never be surprised when a mob enrages and have to shift what you are doing.</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform2"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8">Posting from San Diego, CA</td></tr></table>
