		   <br /><nobr><span id="notbold">Score</span>: Good [4.02]</nobr><br /><br /><a href="/cgi-bin/pm.pl?action=addtolist&addname=gbaji&type=Address" id="fs8"><img src="/shared/plus.gif" border="0" align="middle" height="9" width="9" alt="Add to address book"> Add to address book</a><br /><img src="/shared/transp.gif" width="135" border="0" height="1"></td><td valign="top" class="mform" width="100%"><p><blockquote><b id="fs8">Teleos wrote:</b><hr size="1" /><br>Now.. how to explain all this to folk in a pickup group. Hmmmm.<hr size="1" /></blockquote><br><br>A good tank alleviates all of that. I spent an evening helping out people get fabled FBSS a couple weekends ago. What I'd do is simply turn the mob so it's backside was facing the rest of the group and backed the mob into the corner down the first hall towards the fenzy room (which is generally clear of spawns). No one had the opportunity to be on the wrong side of the mob.<br><br>Beyond that a simple &quot;eveyone who's not the MT on the back of the mob&quot; yelled out regularly enough should do the trick. Anyone who doesn't do that will die pretty quick when the mob enrages, and then you just point out that if they'd not been on the wrong side of the mob, they wouldn't have died.<br><br>I don't really go with the generic &quot;turn off autoattack at 10%&quot; rule. Some mobs enrage earlier then that. Some later. In most groups, the majority of your dps will come from melee damage. There's no sense killing that for no reason. A good tank will be watching for the enrage message and have his hand on the autoattack button ready to turn it off instantly. If things are really dicey in terms of damage I'm taking, I will just turn off autoattack anyway, but as a general rule, I don't do it until I see the mob enrage. It's my personal opinion that if anyone else needs to turn off attack during enrage, they are doing something wrong. I'm also reasonably certain that anyone who doesn't know enough to fight on the backside of a mob is likely to not also think about turning off attack to avoid enrage. If you know about enrage, then just get on the backside of the mob and you're done.<br><br>Do it right all the time and you don't have to make any exceptions when fighting a particular type of mob. But that's just my opinion...</p></td></td></tr><tr><td colspan="2" class="mform"><table border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0" width="100%"><tr><td id="fs8">Posting from San Diego, CA</td></tr></table>
